Cai Chang  
(1900–1990)  

Cai Chang, formerly known as Cai Zong'e, was born in a poor landlord family in Xianfeng County, Hunan Province (now called Xinhua County). In her early years, she was influenced and educated by her eldest brother Cai Hesen and played a significant role in leading workers' movements and promoting women's emancipation in China.  

In 1919, she and Xiang Jingyu engaged in the May Fourth Movement. Together, they organized the Hunan Women's Movement and worked in the Labor Movement. In the autumn of 1922, she joined the Communist Party of China. Over her life, she successively served as the head of the Shanghai Women's Department of the All-China Federation of Trade Unions, the Women’s Section Chief of the Jiangxi Soviet Government, and Chairwoman of the Central Women's Movement Leadership Commission.  

Long-standing, unyielding, and dedicated to women’s liberation and the Communist cause, she contributed greatly to the development of national women’s careers, leading various important efforts for the People's Republic of China nation-building.
